fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Remark. Holds with equality if and only if
f is linear on \mathcal {X}
X is a constant almost surely.

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);

fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Proof. 
Note that 

\begin {align*}
 D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P || Q) &= \mathbb {E}_P \left [\log \left (\frac {P(x)}{Q(x)}\right )\right ] \\
&= \mathbb {E}_P \left [-\log \left (\frac {Q(x)}{P(x)}\right )\right ] \\
\end {align*}

By Jensen's Inequality,

  \begin {align*}
    D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P || Q) &\geq  -\log  \left (\mathbb {E}_P \left [\frac {Q(x)}{P(x)}\right ]\right ) = 0
  \end {align*}

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(200, 55, 45, 0.85);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(200, 55, 45, 0.06);

margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 140, 120, 0.9);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 140, 120, 0.06);

margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);

fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Proof. 
Define p_i = \frac {a_i}{A}, q_i = \frac {b_i}{B}, then 

\begin {align*}
  D_{\mathrm {KL}}(p || q) &= \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {B a_i}{A b_i}} \\
  &= \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} - \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {A}{B}} \\
  &= \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} - \log {\frac {A}{B}} \\
\end {align*}

By Gibb's inequality,

\begin {align*}
  \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} - \log {\frac {A}{B}} \geq  0
  &\implies 
  \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} \geq  \log {\frac {A}{B}} \\
  &\iff 
  A \sum  a_i \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} \geq  A \log {\frac {A}{B}}
\end {align*}

as desired.

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
The optimal estimator g^* : \mathcal {Y} \to  \mathcal {X} is

\begin {align*}
  g^*(y) = \arg \max _{x \in  \mathcal {X}} P_{X | Y}(x | y)
\end {align*}

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);

fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Proof. 
    Recall that

    \begin {align*}
      P_{e}(g) &= \sum _{x}\sum _y P_{XY}(x, y) \cdot  \mathbf {1}_{x \neq  g(y)} \\
      &= \sum _{y} P_Y(y) \sum _{x} P_{X|Y}(x|y) \mathbf {1}_{x \neq  g(y)} \\
      &= \sum _{y} P_Y(y) (1 - P_{X|Y}(g(y)|y)) \\
    \end {align*}

To minimize this, we take

  \begin {align*}
    g^*(y) = \arg \max _{x} P_{X|Y}(x | y)
  \end {align*}

as desired.

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);

fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Proof. 
Use chain rule to expand I(U; (V, W)) in two ways i.e. 

  \begin {align*}
    I(U; (V, W)) = I(U; V) + I(U; W | V) = I(U; W) + I(U; V | W)
  \end {align*}

Since U \to  V \to  W is a Markov chain, the conditional independence (U \perp  W) \mid  V makes I(U; W | V) = 0. Therefore,

\begin {align*}
  I(U; V)  &= I(U; W) + I(U; V | W) \\
&\geq  I(U; W)
\end {align*}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Suppose that X \iff  Y \iff  \hat {X} and let p_e = \mathbb {P}(X \neq  \hat {X}). Then, we have 

    \begin {align*}
      H(p_e) + p_e \log (|\mathcal {X}| - 1) \geq  H(X \mid  \hat {X}) \geq  H(X \mid  Y)
    \end {align*}

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);

fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Proof. 
    By Chebyshev's Inequality,

    \begin {align*}
      \mathbb {P}(|\hat {X} - \mu | > a) \leq  -\frac {\sigma ^2}{a^2}
    \end {align*}

    Since X_i's are independent, 
\mathrm {Var}[\hat {X}] = \frac {1}{n^2} \sum _{i = 1}^{n} \mathrm {Var}[X_i]
    Therefore,

    \begin {align*}
      \lim _{n \to  \infty } \mathbb {P}(|\hat {X} - \mu | > a) \leq  \lim _{n \to  \infty }-\frac {\sigma ^2}{n a^2} \to  0
    \end {align*}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Let \{X_{n}:n\geq 1\} denote i.i.d. \mathcal {X}-valued r.v. with distribution P_{X}. Then,


\begin {align*}
 \lim _{n\to \infty }-\frac {1}{n}\log  p_{X^{n}}(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}) &= \lim _{n \to  \infty } -\frac {1}{n} \log  \prod _{i = 1}^{n} P_X(X_i) \\
 &= \mathbb {E}_{X \sim  p_X}[-\log  p_X(X)] \\ 
 &= H(X)
\end {align*}

Equivalently, for large n

  \begin {align*}
    \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon 
  \end {align*}

with high probability.

Fix an \epsilon >0. Then, an \epsilon -typical set with respect to the pmf p_{X}, denoted by A_{\epsilon }^{(n)}, is defined as
\left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon  \right \}
Alternatively,
A_{\epsilon ^{(n)}} = \left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  2^{-n(H(X) + \epsilon )} \leq  p_{X^n}(X^n) \leq  2^{-n(H(X) - \epsilon )}\right \}

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
